Darstellung als Barplot (1 Layer)

Wir kÃ¶nnen dieses Ergebnis auch grafisch darstellen. Hierbei verwenden wir einen Layer:

  geom_bar(data = nobel.perc, mapping = aes(x = gender, y = perc),

Ein letztes Beispiel III

year.rel <- nobel %>%
  filter(gender != "org") %>%
  group_by(year, gender) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%           # Anteil Frauen & MÃ¤nner
  ungroup() %>%                        # Wir brauchen die Gruppierung nur nach Jahr
  group_by(year) %>%                  
  mutate(total = sum(count)) %>%       # Gesamtsumme an Preise
  filter(gender != "female") %>%       # "Frauen" benÃ¶tigen wir nicht mehr
  mutate(relative = total / count - 1) # count: Anteil MÃ¤nner, total: Gesamtzahl | total / count

Ein âschÃ¶nerâ Plot (3 Layer) I

finplot <- ggplot() +
  geom_line(data = year.rel, 
            mapping = aes(x = year, y = relative),
            stat = "identity") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = mean(year.rel$relative), color = "red", size = 1) +
  annotate(geom = "text", label = "Reading example: \n 0.5 women for each male \n award winner in 2008.", x = 1991, y = 0.48) +
  labs(title = "The gender divide of the Nobel Prize",
       subtitle = "How many females come on each male Nobel Prize Lareaute?",
       caption = "The red line indicates the mean (0.056). \n No prizes were awarded from 1940-1942. \n Source: Nobelprize.org",
       x = "",
       y = "") +
  theme_hc() # Package "ggthemes"
